TY  - JOUR
T1  - An Economic Model for the Division of Labor
AU  - Kilbridge, Maurice
AU  - Wester, Leon
Y1  - 1966/02/01
PY  - 1966
DA  - 1966/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.12.6.B255
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.12.6.B255
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - B-255
EP  - B-269
VL  - 12
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The division of labor in assembly is facilitated by the conveyor line. Workers are stationed along the line on which the frame of the product being assembled moves. The total job is broken into elements of work and assigned in approximately equal shares to the workers on the line. Each operator adds his share of work as the product passes him. The measure of the division of labor is the amount of time the product spends at each operator's work station. This period is commonly called the ?cycle time.? The problem of the economic extent of the division of labor is to determine the optimum cycle time, or that which yields the lowest unit direct labor cost of assembly.
AB  - The division of labor in assembly is facilitated by the conveyor line. Workers are stationed along the line on which the frame of the product being assembled moves. The total job is broken into elements of work and assigned in approximately equal shares to the workers on the line. Each operator adds his share of work as the product passes him. The measure of the division of labor is the amount of time the product spends at each operator's work station. This period is commonly called the ?cycle time.? The problem of the economic extent of the division of labor is to determine the optimum cycle time, or that which yields the lowest unit direct labor cost of assembly.
